1 6. “Provider of special education” means a school within a
2 school district or charter school that provides education or services
3 to pupils with disabilities or any other entity that is responsible for
4 providing education or services to a pupil with a disability for a
5 school district or charter school.
6 7. “Pupil who receives early intervening services” means a
7 person enrolled in kindergarten or grades 1 to 12, inclusive, who is
8 not a pupil with a disability but who needs additional academic and
9 behavioral support to succeed in a regular school program.
10 8. “Pupil with a disability” means a “child with a disability,” as
11 that term is defined in 20 U.S.C. § 1401(3)(A), who is under 22
12 years of age.
13 9. “Response to scientific, research-based intervention” means
14 a collaborative process which assesses a pupil’s response to
15 scientific, research-based intervention that is matched to the needs
16 of a pupil and that systematically monitors the level of performance
17 and rate of learning of the pupil over time for the purpose of making
18 data-based decisions concerning the need of the pupil for
19 increasingly intensified services.
20 10. “Specific learning disability” means a disorder in one or
21 more of the basic psychological processes involved in understanding
22 or using spoken or written language which is not primarily the result
23 of a visual, hearing or motor impairment, intellectual disability,
24 serious emotional disturbance, or an environmental, cultural or
25 economic disadvantage. Such a disorder may manifest itself in an
26 imperfect ability to listen, think, speak, read, write, spell or perform
27 mathematical calculations. The term includes, without limitation,
28 perceptual disabilities, brain injury, minimal brain dysfunction,
29 dyslexia and developmental aphasia.
30 Sec. 3. The provisions of NRS 354.599 do not apply to any
